## Social and Political Structures

Computational thinking is within our political system. Algorithmic targeting is rich in the media outlets which flood out daily lives targeting and influencing those who are known to be on the fence, as with Cambridge Analytica. Mario Carpo says modern generative scientifc methods _show surprising affinities with the anti-scientific ideology of today’s alt-right._ I am interested in the surveillance which is necessary for data collection and how this has almost become normalised (in how we operate online & with IOT devices). The acceptance of surveillance in our lives must be having knock-on effects, and are the reasons why Alexa/Cortana/Siri are able to function for "free". 

* Data Colonialism: Rethinking Big Data’s Relation to the Contemporary Subject — Nick Couldry, Ulises A. Mejias


## Space — Digital Self?

Looking at the differences between the physical landscape that we inhabit, and the physical boundaries that come with that, and comparing this to the online/digital landscape and it's own boundaries and landscape. How does one situate themselves in both, can they? Bratton uses the term _composite user_.

Looking a Lefebvre's ideas of space, I'd like to look at how computation has furthur complicated, or perhaps simplified his notion of the _logico-epistemological space_. Are we able to _read_ the space we have produced and decode it, as Lefebvre says.

What are the causes and limitations of this space given that most of the un-real spaces which we know and inhabit, are hosted on Amazon servers or mediated by social media apps? Are we able to navigate freely, or are we stuck within bounded walls which we cannot see?

* The Black Stack - Benjamin Bratton
* The Production of Space – Henri Lefebvre  

## Social and Political Structures

What is the impact computational thinking has had on democracy, and what we think of as democracy. The democratic system we have had for many years has morphed into something many people now see as undemocratic (David Van Reybrouck). Is the rise of computation actually shining a light on this, or was computation and it's uses accountable for Trump and Brexit? The internet was hailed as a democratic utopia where free speech is the only language - we know that this space never lived up to it's hopes and dreams, and vast swathes on the internet landscape are now subverted/controlled/mediated/filtered - but is it still a beacon of hope in a failing real-world? Many young politicians are gaining traction and are using the online world again to gain a following (AOC), is this enough to combat the big money and big data behind the Trump administration or Putin's reign.

* Can an Algorithm be Agnostic? — Kate Crawford
* Against Elections — David Van Reybrouck

